column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers remained similar as agents offered 1065 liveweight cattle. Quality remains extremely mixed as female cattle were again offered in large numbers with more 2 score cattle presented. The usual trade and processor buyers were active along with feeders and restockers with plainer cattle reflecting an easing trend. The few better conditioned cattle sold generally firm for type and condition.

Vealer steers sold from 330c to 345c with heifers fetching 280c/kg. Yearling steers sold from 250c to 360c as heifers ranged from 140c to 349c/kg.

Manufacturing steers sold from 200c to 350c as grown steers ranged from 259c to 381c with grown heifers fetching 223c to 357c/kg. Light beef cows sold from 130c to 190c, medium dairy breeds ranged from 213c to 239c as medium beef types ranged from 120c to 301c. Heavy beef cows sold from 211c to331c as dairy breeds ranged from 217c to 265c/kg. Bulls sold from 240c to 321c/kg.

Market reporter: John Traeger.
